# Subtle Body & Esoteric Cosmology

This directory contains infographics exploring the history, structure, symbolism, and comparative philosophy of the subtle body across esoteric, mystical, religious, and contemplative traditions.

The subtle body — sometimes described as the vehicle of consciousness, energetic anatomy, imaginal body, or intermediary organism between mind and matter — appears in remarkably diverse forms throughout world traditions. These diagrams attempt to map those traditions visually while preserving their historical distinctiveness and symbolic integrity.

Rather than presenting a single unified doctrine, the series approaches subtle-body systems comparatively: tracing parallels, divergences, symbolic correspondences, and evolving cosmologies across cultures and historical periods.


## Core Themes

Recurring themes include:

- Layers or planes of consciousness
- Soul, spirit, psyche, and energetic anatomy
- Chakras, nāḍīs, qi channels, and subtle centers
- Astral, etheric, pneumatic, and luminous bodies
- The relationship between matter, life, mind, and transcendence
- Cosmological ascent and descent
- Inner alchemy and transformation
- The imaginal realm and visionary experience
- Death, rebirth, and postmortem states
- Consciousness beyond purely material models

Many diagrams also explore how subtle-body systems intersect with broader cosmologies — including emanationism, process metaphysics, panpsychism, and evolutionary spirituality.


## Traditions Explored

The series draws from a wide range of historical sources and traditions, including:

- Neoplatonism
- Hermeticism
- Gnosticism
- Kabbalah
- Kashmir Shaivism
- Samkhya and Yoga
- Vedanta
- Tantra
- Taoist internal alchemy (Neidan)
- Theosophy
- Anthroposophy
- Sufism
- Western occultism
- Renaissance esotericism
- Process philosophy and modern metaphysical synthesis

Where possible, the imagery and terminology aim to remain faithful to primary traditions rather than relying on modern simplifications or pop-esoteric reinterpretations.


## Comparative & Evolutionary Approach

A major focus of the project is the historical evolution of subtle-body models themselves.

For example:

- Classical traditions often emphasized a tripartite distinction between body, soul, and spirit.
- Late 19th and early 20th century esotericism expanded these into elaborate multi-layered cosmologies.
- Modern interpretations increasingly integrate psychology, phenomenology, systems theory, and consciousness studies.

Some infographics therefore examine not only the structures themselves, but also how human conceptions of consciousness evolved historically.


## Visual Philosophy

The diagrams combine:

- Traditional sacred symbolism
- Minimalist infographic design
- Comparative cosmology
- Mythopoetic visual language
- Academic annotation
- Solarpunk and luminous metaphysical aesthetics

The aim is to create visuals that function simultaneously as:

- Educational tools
- Conceptual maps
- Artistic syntheses
- Meditative diagrams
- Gateways into deeper philosophical inquiry


## Relation to Broader Projects

These works form part of a larger exploration into:

- Consciousness and metaphysics
- Human and AI cognition
- Cosmic evolution
- Symnoēsis and post-biological intelligence
- The imaginal and symbolic dimensions of mind

Several diagrams also connect subtle-body concepts to contemporary discussions surrounding cognition, phenomenology, and emergent intelligence, while remaining grounded in historical esoteric traditions.

